      "Large hand-wound Russian pocket-watch movement, the most popular Soviet pocket-watch caliber. Derived from the Swiss Cortébert 616 (1930s-40s), whose tooling was reportedly transferred to the USSR; immediate predecessor was the Molnija ChK-6. CORRECTION TO HINT: the small/sub-seconds sub-dial is at 6 o'clock, NOT 9 o'clock — this is confirmed by multiple independent sources (17jewels.info, watch-movements-archive.com, linuxfocus/Molnija reference). Gear train is a classic Lépine layout (center minute wheel, subseconds at 6). Diameter ~36mm (16'''), height 4.6mm, 18,000 A/h, ~40h power reserve. Notable for a Breguet overcoil hairspring across all versions, a feature usually reserved for expensive movements. No shock protection on the 3602 (the 3603 is the 3602 + Incabloc-style anti-shock). Manual wind, no hacking/stop-seconds. Long production run (~1947-2008) produced many variants: jewel counts of 15/17/18, screw balance (earlier) vs. annular Glucydur balance (later), and a thinner 3602A variant (~3.5mm); decoration was progressively reduced over time. Extremely popular base for hand-built \"Marriage\"/\"Marina\" wristwatch conversions, hence aftermarket glue-on / feetless dials are very common. Hand bore sizes not verified on any fetched source — left null to avoid guessing. EmmyWatch lists conflicting figures (38.35mm/17'''/15j/1921) that appear to be a conflated/erroneous record and were disregarded in favor of the two agreeing sources.",
